metadata.abstract: The text explores the ordinary repertory of Aquileia and Cividale, analyzing the dissemination and categorization of melodies within these sources. It highlights the influence of German and Central European traditions on the Aquileian repertory, contrasting it with Italian sources and noting regional variations. The study emphasizes the complexity of defining the Aquileian tradition due to intercultural influences and suggests further research to refine the understanding of these musical sources.

It is perhaps unusual when concerning the observations and conclusions of an examination the author himself warns the audience. I emphasized in advance that the methods used in this paper might be risky to a certain extent. Already the retrieval of the information from the catalogs itself and the quasi-reconstruction of virtual sources by deduction is problematic. Already the material the analysis focused on is not beyond doubt reliable and what is more important, it is only to a very limited extent suitable for analyzing the melodies in their real context. And the evaluation of the sources requires several aspects other than the mere occurrence or absence of a certain melody. For example, my own research proved that distribution of the Curiale melodies in the sources of the material is not so important. The distribution of the sources, the assignment of them to certain feasts, the pairing of them, the compilation of cycles from them and last but not least the actual variance of the melodies all together outline a physiognomy of repertory that could be characteristic of a diocese or a consuetudo. The other aspect I neglected here to a certain extent is the chronology. As Camillo Oswald, among others, emphasizes, there is a not negligible difference between the 12th and 14th and 15th century state of the Aquileian tradition. Among my observations there may be cases where the differences are the consequences of chronological rather than geographical or institutional distance of the sources. However, the tables presented in the foregoing reveal the character of the Aquileian ordinary repertory. Show its significant points and are quite promising as to make the picture more accurate and convincing later on by examining the other aspects mentioned above. Thank you very much.

I emphasized in advance that the methods used in this paper might be risky to a certain extent. For example, my own research proved that distribution of the Curiale melodies in the sources of the material is not so important. The distribution of the sources, the assignment of them to certain feasts, the pairing of them, the compilation of cycles from them and last but not least the actual variance of the melodies all together outline a physiognomy of repertory that could be characteristic of a diocese or a consuetudo. The other aspect I neglected here to a certain extent is the chronology. As Camillo Oswald, among others, emphasizes, there is a not negligible difference between the 12th and 14th and 15th century state of the Aquileian tradition. Among my observations there may be cases where the differences are the consequences of chronological rather than geographical or institutional distance of the sources.
